                                    "content": " of BMSB, establishing a satisfactory confidence level overall. On the other hand, the NNs have developed limited abilities in contouring the BMSB according to "
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        175,
                                        2009,
                                        1225,
                                        2950
                                    ],
                                    "type": "inline_equation",
                                    "content": "\\mathrm{mAP_{0.5}^{0.95}}"
                                },
                                {
                                    "bbox": [
                                        175,
                                        2009,
                                        1225,
                                        2950
                                    ],
                                    "type": "text",
                                    "content": " because they are less robust when the IoU increases. In other words, the majority of predictions overlap partially with the ground truth. This represents a predictable outcome due to the limited size of the BMSB with respect to the entire image. For monitoring purposes, recognizing all instances inside the frame, i.e., achieving high recall, is more important than accurately contouring a bug, i.e., achieving high IoU. However, it noteworthy that both YOLOv9 and YOLOv10 demonstrate improved IoU values between prediction and ground truth, suggesting a clear enhancement with previous releases. Moreover, in comparison with the results in [20] where entire images are simply resized and fed to the model, the current implementation of the slicing mechanism allows a boost in the performance, specifically in the recall. Indeed, image slicing prevents information losses since it retains every pixel of the original image."
